ign=\"center\" |19\n| align=\"center\" |23\n| align=\"center\" |21\n| align=\"center\" |60\n| align=\"center\" |153\n| align=\"center\" |737\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Davis Cup player}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berasategui, Alberto}}\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Andorra]]\n[[Category:Spanish male tennis players]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Arrigorriaga]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in tennis]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games silver medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games bronze medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1991 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1993 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Biscay]]\n[[Category:Basque tennis players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{spanish name|Berasategui|Salazar}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name = Alberto Berasategui\n|image =\n|country = {{ESP}}\n|residence = [[Bellaterra]], Spain\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1973|6|28}}\n|birth_place = [[Bilbao]], Spain\n|height = {{height|m=1.72}}\n|turnedpro = 1991\n|retired = May 2001\n|plays = Right-handed (one and two-handed backhand)\n|careerprizemoney = $4,676,187\n|singlesrecord = 278\u2013199\n|singlestitles = 14\n|highestsinglesranking = No. 7 (14 November 1994)\n|AustralianOpenresult = QF ([[1998 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1998]])\n|FrenchOpenresult = F ([[1994 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1994]])\n|Wimbledonresult = 1R ([[2000 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2000]])\n|USOpenresult = 2R ([[1993 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1993]], [[1996 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1996]])\n|Othertournaments = yes\n|MastersCupresult = RR ([[1994 ATP Tour World Championships \u2013 Singles|1994]])\n|doublesrecord = 47\u201359\n|doublestitles = 1\n|highestdoublesranking = No. 55 (6 October 1997)\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult = 1R ([[1998 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|1998]], [[2000 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2000]])\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult = 1R ([[1999 French Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|1999]])\n|USOpenDoublesresult = 3R ([[1997 US Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|1997]])\n}}\n\n'''Alberto Berasategui Salazar''' (born 28 June 1973) is a former professional [[tennis player]] from Spain. He won 14 singles titles and achieved a career-high singles [[ATP Rankings|ranking]] of world No. 7 in November 1994.\n\n==Tennis career==\nBerasategui won a total of 14 top-level singles titles and one tour doubles title. He won at least one singles title for six consecutive years (1993\u20131998). He began playing tennis at age seven and was the European junior champion in 1991. He turned professional later that year, and won his first top-level singles title in 1993, two years later. \n\nIn 1994, Berasategui reached nine finals, winning seven of them. He also reached his first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] final at the [[French Open]], where he defeated [[Wayne Ferreira]], [[C\u00e9dric Pioline]], [[Yevgeny Kafelnikov]], [[Javier Frana]], [[Goran Ivani\u0161evi\u0107]] and [[Magnus Larsson]] to face fellow Spaniard and defending champion [[Sergi Bruguera]] who defeated him in four sets.\n\nBerasategui retired from the professional tour in May 2001, having had persistent wrist injuries since his match with [[Hern\u00e1n Gumy]] at the [[ATP Bologna Outdoor|Bologna]] tournament in June 1998. The injuries had an adverse effect on his results and form, and had caused his consistency and ranking to decline. He also suffered severe cramps of unknown origin in long matches.\n\n==Playing style==\nBererasategui was known for his extreme western grip, known as the \"Hawaiian grip\", where his unusual hold on the racket would allow him to hit both forehands and backhands with the same side of the racket.<ref>Roetert, P. & J.L. Groppel: ''World-Class Tennis Technique'', p. 156. Human Kinetics, 2001.</ref><ref name=\"oregonlive\">{{cite web |title=In praise of weirdness: Where have you gone, Alberto Berasategui? |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/tennis/2010/04/in_praise_of_weirdness_alberto_berasategui.html |website=OregonLive.com |date=21 April 2010}}</ref> This helped him on clay, but he did not have much of an impact on other surfaces except for a quarterfinals appearance at the [[1998 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1998 Australian Open]], after having beaten world No. 2, [[Patrick Rafter]] in four sets in the third round, and came back from two sets down to beat the [[1995 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1995]], [[2000 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2000]], and [[2001 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2001]] [[Australian Open]] champion, former and future world No. 1, [[Andre Agassi]], in the fourth round. He lost in quarterfinals to [[Marcelo R\u00edos]] after winning a tight first-set tiebreak.<ref name=\"oregonlive\"/>\n\n==Grand Slam finals==\n===Singles: 1 (1 runner-up)===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!width=\"80\"|Outcome\n!width=\"50\"|Year\n!width=\"160\"|Championship\n!width=\"75\"|Surface\n!width=\"180\"|Opponent\n!width=\"140\"|Score\n|-bgcolor=\"#EBC2AF\"\n| bgcolor=\"FFA07A\"| Runner-up || [[1994 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1994]] || [[French Open]] || Clay || {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Sergi Bruguera]] || 3\u20136, 5\u20137, 6\u20132, 1\u20136\n|}\n\n==Career finals==\n===Singles: 23 (14 titles, 9 runner-ups)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" \n|- \n| '''Legend'''\n|- style=\"background:#f3e6d7;\"\n| Grand Slam (0\u20131)\n|- style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n| ATP Masters Series (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#d4f1c5;\"\n| ATP Championship Series (1\u20131)\n|-\n| ATP Tour (13\u20137)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:45px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\" class=\"unsortable\"|W/L\n!style=\"width:60px\"|Date\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Tournament\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:15